==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Beryl
<hw>Ber"yl</hw> <pr>(b⟦ecr⟧r"⟦icr⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>b⟦eacute⟧ryl</ets>, OF. <ets>beril</ets>, L. <ets>beryllus</ets>,
Gr. <grk>bh`ryllos</grk>, prob. fr. Skr. <ets>vai⟦dsdot⟧⟦umac⟧rya</ets>.
Cf. <er>Brilliant</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A mineral of great
hardness, and, when transparent, of much beauty. It occurs in hexagonal
prisms, commonly of a green or bluish green color, but also yellow,
pink, and white. It is a silicate of aluminum and beryllium. The
<stype>aquamarine</stype> is a transparent, sea-green variety used as a
gem. The <stype>emerald</stype> is another variety highly prized in
jewelry, and distinguished by its deep color, which is probably due to
the presence of a little oxide of chromium.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Berylline</ent>⟦br⟧
